name: HD 95089
scenarioDescription:
The HD 95089 Exoplanetary System


Overview

HD 95089 is a star with 1.54 times the mass of the Sun, and 5.08 times its radius. It is located 448.33 light years away from the solar system.

HD 95089 is known to have 2 exoplanets in orbit around it.


Exoplanets in the HD 95089 system


HD 95089 b

HD 95089 b was discovered by the W. M. Keck Observatory observatory using the radial velocity method. Its semi-major axis is 1.36 astronomical units, as compared to Earth's which is 1 astronomical unit. The mass of HD 95089 b is 400.68 times the mass of Earth. At more than 50 Earth masses, HD 95089 b is a gas giant, a planet whose mass is mostly made up of hydrogen and helium, like Jupiter and Saturn in our solar system.


HD 95089 c

HD 95089 c was discovered by the W. M. Keck Observatory observatory using the radial velocity method. Its semi-major axis is 3.33 astronomical units, as compared to Earth's which is 1 astronomical unit. The mass of HD 95089 c is 1097.1000000000001 times the mass of Earth. At more than 50 Earth masses, HD 95089 c is a gas giant, a planet whose mass is mostly made up of hydrogen and helium, like Jupiter and Saturn in our solar system.
description: 3D visualisation and gravity simulation of the exoplanet system HD 95089, which contains 2 planets and was discovered by W. M. Keck Observatory.
